        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="TNYAdobeCaslonPro, 'Times New Roman', serif;" color="#000000">
          <h2 style="
              font-size: 24px;
              line-height: 1.2;
              font-weight: 400;
              margin-top: 2px !important;
            ">Sol searching</h2>  
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
         In 2017, Hurricane Maria ripped through Puerto Rico, leaving behind a battered economy. Amid the devastation, most saw tragedy. But Brock Pierce saw a possibility. By the time he arrived in Puerto Rico that year, <strong>Pierce was already a well-known name in the blockchain world:</strong> an investor in experimental ventures, co-founder of Tether and EOS, and a veteran of several spectacular business flameouts. He was about to lead an ideological migration. 
          </p>
        </mj-text> 

        <mj-image border-radius="10px" padding="10px 12px 14px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.businesshistory.co/email/images/brock-pierce-2020-presidential-run-former-child-actor.png" alt="Brock Pierce, former child actor from “The Mighty Ducks” and “First Kid,” announced he is running for president in 2020" href="https://www.businesshistory.co" />
         <mj-text padding="0px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#A9A7AF">
          <p style="font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.2; color: #A9A7AF;">
            <i>Brock Pierce, former child actor from “The Mighty Ducks” and “First Kid,” announced he is running for president in 2020. Credits: Buena Vista Pictures/Courtesy Everett Collection</i>
          </p>
        </mj-text>

        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">

          Alongside other newly minted crypto millionaires, he began snapping up property and pitching a utopian vision, one of a <strong>blockchain-powered society called “Puertopia.” That name didn’t last, as they rebranded it to “Sol.”</strong> By early 2018, dozens of crypto entrepreneurs were selling their California homes and shipping out to Puerto Rico to capitalize on generous tax incentives. 
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
          But the dream quickly became messier. Pierce purchased at least 14 properties, including a hurricane-damaged beach resort, an old hospital, and a children’s museum turned “idea space.” <strong>None of them materialized into the crypto-powered oases they were hyped up to be.</strong> The hospital struggled with basic operations. The museum sat empty. The resort led to <a 
style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #8C3321; color: black;" href="https://link.businesshistory.co/bh-10-05-2025-lawsuits-unpaid-bills-and-loss-of-ownership" target="_blank">lawsuits, unpaid bills, and losing ownership</a> to a disgruntled partner. It wouldn’t be the first time Pierce’s big visions ran aground. Nor would it halt him.
          </p>
        </mj-text>
      </mj-column> 
