          <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="TNYAdobeCaslonPro, 'Times New Roman', serif;" color="#000000">
          <h2 style="
              font-size: 24px;
              line-height: 1.2;
              font-weight: 400;
              margin-top: 2px !important;
            ">The relentless pursuit of Pierce</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
          Born in Minnesota, Pierce began his career as a child actor. You might remember him as young Gordon Bombay in <i>The Mighty Ducks</i> or the president’s son in First Kid. But by 16, he had retired from acting. He joined <strong>Marc Collins-Rector and Chad Schackley to establish Digital Entertainment Network</strong> (DEN), a company that collapsed under the weight of sexual assault allegations.
         </p>
         </mj-text>
         <mj-image border-radius="10px" padding="10px 12px 14px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.businesshistory.co/email/images/brock-pierce-east-village-church-puerto-rican-monastery-club.png" alt="Former presidential candidate Brock Pierce wants to convert a former East Village church into a rental residence, he's already turning a former Puerto Rican monastery into a club" href="https://www.businesshistory.co" />
         <mj-text padding="0px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#A9A7AF">
          <p style="font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.2; color: #A9A7AF;">
            <i>Former presidential candidate Brock Pierce wants to convert a former East Village church into a rental residence, he's already turning a former Puerto Rican monastery into a club. Credits: James Messerschmidt</i>
          </p>
        </mj-text>
         <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
          Next came Internet Gaming Entertainment (IGE), a trailblazer selling digital currency for online games. Then came ZAM (sold to Tencent), Titan Gaming (rebranded as Playsino), and the crypto boom. In 2013, <strong>Pierce co-founded Blockchain Capital</strong>, one of the earliest venture firms focused solely on blockchain. He worked with Mastercoin, which pioneered the ICO model and ignited a global fundraising craze.</p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
          <a 
style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #8C3321; color: black;" href="https://link.businesshistory.co/bh-10-05-2025-he-co-founded-tether" target="_blank">He co-founded Tether</a>, which is one of the most traded cryptocurrencies, and Block. One, which raised a mind-blowing $4B. At one point, <i>Forbes</i> estimated his net worth between $700M and $1.1B. Just when you thought Brock Pierce couldn’t surprise you anymore, <strong>he launched an independent run for president in 2020</strong>, just a day after Kanye West announced his bizarre bid, in the middle of a global pandemic.</p>
          </mj-text>
          <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="TNYAdobeCaslonPro, 'Times New Roman', serif;" color="#000000">
          <h2 style="
              font-size: 24px;
              line-height: 1.2;
              font-weight: 400;
              margin-top: 2px !important;
            ">Presidential election and rocky road</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
         <strong>Brock Pierce’s 2020 presidential run wasn’t about heading the White House</strong> but about challenging the status quo and <a 
style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #8C3321; color: black;" href="https://link.businesshistory.co/bh-10-05-2025-reimagining-the-system" target="_blank">reimagining the system</a>. He even drew on Bhutan’s Gross National Happiness index to propose a more human-centered measure of national development. He also made history as the first US presidential candidate to receive a vote via blockchain. While his campaign didn’t gain electoral traction, the core of his vision, bringing crypto into mainstream governance, is unfolding under Donald Trump’s second term.</p>
<!-- 
          <mj-image border-radius="10px" padding="10px 12px 14px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.businesshistory.co/email/images/trump-taj-mahal-liquidation-sale-crowds-expected-60-days.png" alt="The Trump Taj Mahal liquidation sale is expected to attract hundreds of people each day during the 60-day sale" href="https://www.businesshistory.co" />
           <mj-text padding="0px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#A9A7AF">
          <p style="font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.2; color: #A9A7AF;">
            <i>The Trump Taj Mahal liquidation was expected to attract hundreds of people each day during the 60-day window. Credits: Craig Matthews/Press of Atlantic City</i>
          </p>
        </mj-text> -->

          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
          Ironically, the disruptive, digital-first future Pierce imagined is beginning to take shape under the leadership of a former president who once seemed worlds apart from that vision. And yet, for all his innovation and foresight, <strong>Pierce’s ventures often seem to end in chaos, conflict, or courtroom drama</strong>. In Puerto Rico, lawsuits from unpaid partners, failed projects, and unrealized promises represent one chapter in the many roles he plays.</p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
          For all the flops, he keeps coming back, raising funds, reinventing industries, and rallying people around newer ideas. Whether he seems as a visionary or a vaporware salesman, there’s no denying his relentlessness, almost irrational persistence. <strong>Pierce’s story reveals that the road to disruption is rarely a straight line</strong>. It’s paved with hype, lawsuits, rebrands, and unfinished hospitals. But if you can stomach the chaos and are willing to keep showing up, you might build something that lasts.</p>
          </mj-text> 
      </mj-column>
